                subsections: [
                    { 
                         subTitle: '',
                         content: `<em><span style="font-weight:900;color:white;text-shadow: 1px 1px 2px grey;background-color:silver;font-size:x-large"font-size:larger">Shree Brahma said:  </span>
                        <ol><li>0 sage, thus I have told you about the prayer to Siva offered by all the devas. How Sati obtained a boon from Siva, you shall now listen with respect.</li>
                        <li>Then, in the month of Asvina (September-October), Sati observed a fast on the eighth day of the bright half and
                        worshipped Siva with great devotion.</li>
                        <li>When her Nanda rites were concluded on the ninth  day (Navami), while she was engrossed in meditation, Siva became visible to her. </li>
                        <li> He was fair-complexioned, ....handsome in appearance, had five faces<noteref1_note1footer>(1) - (264)</note> and three eyes<noteref2_note2footer>(2) - (265)</note>. The crescent moon
                        adorned His forehead. He was in a joyous mood. He had
                        four arms and His neck was blue<noteref3_note3footer>(3) - (266)</note> in colour. He was holding trident and an amulet ( Brahmakavaca) for protection.
                        He was brilliant with dust. His head was comely with the celestial river Ganga. He was gay in all parts of his body.
                        He was the abode of great beauty. His face shone with the brilliance of ten million moons. His lustre matched that of ten million cupids. In every respect His features were such
                        as appeal to all women</li>
                        <li>On seeing Siva directly in such a form she bent her head from shyness and she knelt at his feet.</li>
                        <li>Although He desired her to be his wife, He wished to bestow on her the fruit of her penance. Thus He spoke to her in the state of her penance. </li>
                        <em><span style="font-weight:900;color:darkblue;text-shadow: 3px 3px 2px white;background-color:skyblue;font-size:xx-large"> Isvara (Lord Shiva) said:  </span>
                        <li>0 daughter of Daksa of good rites, I am delighted by these rites you have observed. Choose a boon. I shall grant it whatever it may be.  </li>
                        <em><span style="font-weight:900;color:white;text-shadow: 1px 1px 2px grey;background-color:silver;font-size:x-large"font-size:larger">Shree Brahma said:  </span>
                        <li>Although Siva, the lord of the universe, knew her desire, he said-"Choose a boon." It was because He desired to hear her speak.</li>
                        <li> She too, who was highly bashful, could not speak out her mind as it was covered up by bashfulness.</li>
                        <li>On realising that she was fully immersed in love on hearing Siva's pleasing words, Sankara who was favourably disposed to His devotees was highly pleased.</li>
                        <li>He repeatedly urged her "Speak out the boon you wish to choose, speak out the boon." Siva, the immanent lord, the goal of the good was drawn to Sati by her
                        devotion. </li>
                        <li>Somehow suppressing her bashfulness when Sati spoke "As you please give unto me, 0 bestower of boons,
                        the desired boon or the bridegroom of my desire, without any hindrance," the full-emblemed deity Siva who is favourably disposed to his devotees, did not wait for the completion
                        of her request and said-"you be my wife"</li>
                        <li>On hearing his words embracing the fruits of her cherished desire she kept si1ent. She was highly delighted on obtaining the boon {or bridegroom) stationed in her mind.</li>
                        <li>She stood smiling sweetly before Siva who was full of love. She opened her inmost feelings through various subtle gestures that increased notions of love.</li>
                        <li>Taking up these notions, gestures and feelings, the flavour of love called Srngara entered their hearts.</li>
                        <li>0 celestial sage, by the advent of the flavour of love, a peculiar glow: in the usual manner of worldly sports, was manifest in them as in the star Citra and the moon.<noteref4_note4footer>(4) - (267)</note></li>
                        <li>In the presence of Siva whose body shone with the brilliance of crystal, Sati who had the glossy brilliance of split collyrium, shone like a line of cloud near the moon.</li>
                        <li>The delighted daughter of Daksa with her palms joined frequently in reverence, joyfully spoke to Siva who is favourably disposed to His devotees. </li>
                        <li><em><span style="font-weight:900;color:crimson;text-shadow: 3px 3px 2px pink;background-color:orange;font-size:x-large">Sati Said </span></em>   0 great lord of Devas, lord of the universe,
                        please take me with due marital rites in the presence of my father. </li>
                        <em><span style="font-weight:900;color:white;text-shadow: 1px 1px 2px grey;background-color:silver;font-size:x-large"font-size:larger">Shree Brahma said:  </span>
                        <li>On hearing these words of Sati, Siva, favourably disposed to His devotees, glanced lovingly at her and said- "So be it."</li>
                        <li>The daughter of Daksa bowed to Siva with devotion, sought and received His consent and returned to her mother with a. fascinating gaiety. </li>
                        <li>Siva returned to His hermitage on the ridges of the  Himalayas and began meditations though with difficulty, as
                        He still felt the pangs of love in separation from Sati, the daughter of Daksa</li>
                        <li>Calming his mind somehow, 0 celestial sage, Siva, the bull-emblemed deity, thought of me in the usual conventions of the world.</li>
                        <li>Being thus thought of by the trident-bearing  Siva, I approached Him immediately prodded by Siva's power of meditation.</li>
                        <li>Accompanied by Sarasvati<noteref5_note5footer>(5) - (268)</note> I reached that place on the Himalayan ridge where Siva stayed pining in the
                        anguish of love for Sati.</li>
                        <li>0 celestial sage, seeing me in the company of Sarasvati, lord Siva who was entangled in the clutches of Sati's love said thus :-</li>
                        <em><span style="font-weight:900;color:darkblue;text-shadow: 3px 3px 2px white;background-color:skyblue;font-size:xx-large"> Lord Shiva said:  </span>
                        <li>0 Brahma, since, in the matter of accepting a wife I showed a little selfishness, I have a feeling of possession  in everything connected with self-interest.</li>
                        <li>I have been propitiated by Sati, the daughter of Daksa with devotion. Thanks to the sacred Nanda rites, I have given her a boon.</li>
                        <li>0 Brahma, the boon "0 be my husband" was sought of me by her. Glad at heart in every respect I had  told her "Be my wife."</li>
                        <li>Then Sati, the daughter of Daksa told me like this-"0 lord of the universe, please accept me in the presence
                        of my father.''</li>
                        <li>0 Brahma, that too I granted her as I was satisfied with her devotion, She returned to her mother's house,
                        0 Brahma and I returned here.</li>
                        <li>At my bidding you must approach to him so that he shall give his daughter in marriage to me at once. </li>
                        <li>Exploit all means to cut short her days of separation. 0 adept in every lore, console Daksa</li>
                        <em><span style="font-weight:900;color:white;text-shadow: 1px 1px 2px grey;background-color:silver;font-size:x-large"font-size:larger">Shree Brahma said:  </span>
                        <li>Having concluded the austerities, and secured what she desired as a boon, Sati went home and made obeisance to her father and mother.</li>
                        <li>Her girl friends informed her mother and father about the acquisition of boon by their friend Sati from lord  Siva who was glad at her devotion.</li>
                        <li>The parents who obtained the news through her friends were very glad and celebrated a great festival.</li>
                        <li>The noble Daksa gave as much wealth to brahmins as they desired. The noble Virini gave similar gifts to the blind, the poor and the needy.</li>
                        <li> Virini embraced her daughter on the head and delightfully praised her frequently.</li>
                        <li>After some time had elapsed, Daksa the foremost of those who knew Dharma, thought of the procedure of handing over his daughter to Siva.</li>
                        <li>The great Lord Siva had come here himself. out of his sheer delight. But he has gone back. How will he come again to woo my daughter?</li>
                        <li>Can a person be sent to Siva immediately ? No, this is not proper. If he spurns the offer it will be a fruitless torment.</li>
                        <li>Or shall I worship the same bull-emblemed deity ? He has already granted the boon to her that He, the lord Himself, shall be her husband. Even if He is
                        delighted at my worship, as at my daughter's devotion, he may like everything to be done through some noble mediator.</li>
                        <li>Even as Daksa was constantly thinking like this, I suddenly appeared before him along with Sarasvati.</li>
                        <li>On seeing me Dakksa my son, paid due respects and stood waiting. He gave me a fitting seat to sit on.</li>
                        <li>was worried with thoughts. But he became greatly delighted at my sight. He asked me the purpose of  my visit.
                        <em><span style="font-weight:900;color:maroon;font-size:larger"> Daksa said:  </span>
                        <li>0 creator, preceptor of the universe, be kind and tell me the purpose of your visit to me ?</li>
                        <li>0 creator of worlds, is your visit prompted by your love for your son or for any special task that you have
                        come to my hermitage? I am delighted on seeing you.</li>
                        <em><span style="font-weight:900;color:white;text-shadow: 1px 1px 2px grey;background-color:silver;font-size:x-large"font-size:larger">Shree Brahma said:  </span>
                        <li>0 excellent sage, being asked thus by my son I spoke with a smile thereby delighting the lord of the subjects.</li>
                        <li>0 listen. I shall tell you why I have come here. The wholesome benefit of your progeny is what I desire and what you must also desire.</li>
                        <li>Your daughter has propitiated Siva, the lord of the universe and has secured a boon. The opportune moment for the same has arrived now.</li>
                        <li>It is certainly for your daughter that I have been sent to you by Siva. Listen attentively to your duty conducive to your benefit.</li>
                        <li>After granting the boon, Siva returned. But, ever since, he has not had any mental peace due to separation from your daughter. </li>
                        <li>Kama could not conquer Siva as he did not hit at any vulnerable point although he tried it by means of  his flower-arrows. But He, without being hit by Kama's arrows,
                        has now abandoned meditation on Atman and begun to think of Sati. He is as excited as any other ordinary man.</li>
                        <li>He asks His attendants "where is Sati ?", as He suffers from the pang of separation. When they say "No", He hears the words but soon forgets them and repeats the
                        question.</li>
                        <li>0 son, what has been desired by me before, by you, by Kama and the sages-Marici and others, has been achieved now.</li>
                        <li>Siva was propitiated by your daughter. He now stays in the Himalayan mountains thinking about her and desirous of getting her in order to console her.</li>
                        <li>Just as Siva has been worshipped by her by perforn1ing different rites with Sattvic feelings, so also Sati  is being worshipped by Him.</li>
                        <li> Hence, 0 offer immediately your daughter to Siva for whom she has been intended. Thereby you will get contentment and relief.</li>
                        <li>Through Narada I shall bring Him here. Give her to Him for whom she has been intended.</li>
                        <li>On hearing these words of mine, my son  was highly delighted. He said delightfully. "It IS so. It is so."</li>
                        <li>0 sage, I too delightfully went to the place where Siva was eagerly waiting.</li>
                        <li>At my departure along his wife and  daughter, Daksa felt contented as if he had been filled with nectar. </li>
</ol> <a href=\'#top\'><strong>Back To Top</strong></a></p>`,
