                                { 
                                     subTitle: '',
                                     content: `
                                    <ol> <em><span style="font-weight:900;color:white;text-shadow: 1px 1px 2px grey;background-color:silver;font-size:x-large"font-size:larger">Shree Brahma said:  </span>
                                    <li> Once at the advent of clouds, Daksha's daughter said to Siva who was halting on the ridge of Kailasa mountain. </li>
                                    <em><span style="font-weight:900;color:crimson;text-shadow: 3px 3px 2px pink;background-color:orange;font-size:x-large">Sati said:  </span>
                                    <li>0 lord of devas, 0 Siva my dear husband, please hear my words and do accordingly, 0 bestower of honour.</li>
                                    <li>The most unbearable season of the advent of clouds has arrived with clusters of clouds of diverse hues, and their music reverberating in the sky and the various
                                    quarters.</li>
                                    <li>The speedy gusts of wind scattering sprays of water mingled with nectarine drops from the Kadamba flowers captivate the heart as they blow.</li>
                                    <li>Whose mind will not be agitated by the loud and forceful rumblings of the clouds that release a heavy downpour and have the beams oflightning for their ensign?</li>
                                    <li>Covered by the clouds neither the sun nor the moon is visible. Even the day appears like the night and it distresses those who are separated from their lovers.</li>
                                    <li>0 Siva, tossed about by the gusts of wind the clouds do not remain steady in any place, they rumble and appear as if they would fall on the heads of the people.</li>
                                    <li>Huge trees struck down by the wind appear to dance in the sky, terrifying the cowards and delighting the lover, 0  Siva.</li>
                                    <li>Flocks of cranes above the clouds glossy and blue like the collyrium shine like foams on the surface of Yamuna.</li>
                                    <li>During the close of the nights the circle of lightning appears like the blazing submarine<noteref1_note1footer>(1) - (277)</note> fire in the ocean.</li>
                                    <li>0 odd-eyed Siva, here even in the courtyards of the temples, plants grow; need I mention the growth of plants elsewhere?</li>
                                    <li>With the clusters of clouds dark, silvery and red in colour clinging to the Mandara mountain (peak), Himalaya appears as the ocean of milk with the birds of diverse colours.</li>
                                    <li>Unrivalled splendour has resorted to the Kirhsuka flowers devoid of odour, as (the Goddess of fortune) abandons good people and resorts to the crooked, whether of
                                    high or low birth.</li>
                                    <li>he peacocks are delighted at the sound of the cloud over the Mandara mountain. Their gleeful cackles and out-stretched tails indicate the incessant pleasure of their
                                    heart.</li>
                                    <li>The sweet and delightful sounds of the Cataka birds that are fond of clouds fall upon the way-farers like the arrows of rain-showers causing incessant pain.</li>
                                    <li>See the wickedness perpetrated by the clouds on my body. They are pelting it with hailstones. But they cover and protect the peacocks and Catakas who are their
                                    followers.</li>
                                    <li>On seeing the distress of peacocks and deer from even their friend (sun), the swans go even to the distant Manasa lake on the top of the mountain.</li>
                                    <li>In this troublesome time, even crows and Cakora  birds build their nests. But you don't. Without a home how will you be happy?</li>
                                    <li>0 Pinaka-bearer Siva<noteref2_note2footer>(2) - (278)</note>, let not the great fear  originating from clouds befall us. Hence endeavour for a residence. Do not delay. Heed my words.</li>
                                    <li>0 bull-emblemed God, either in Kailasa or in the  Himalayas or in Mahakasi on the earth you make a befitting habitation. 
                                    </li>
                                    <em><span style="font-weight:900;color:white;text-shadow: 1px 1px 2px grey;background-color:silver;font-size:x-large"font-size:larger">Shree Brahma said:  </span>
                                    <li>Thus advised by Sati frequently Siva laughed provoking a smile from the moon on his head by way of its beams.</li>
                                    <li>Then the high·souled lord Siva who knew all the principles spoke to Sati with a smile breaking his lips· asunder and consoling her. </li>
                                    <em><span style="font-weight:900;color:darkblue;text-shadow: 3px 3px 2px white;background-color:skyblue;font-size:xx-large"> Lord Shiva said:  </span>
                                    <li>"0 my beloved, beautiful woman, clouds will not reach the place where I have to make an abode for you.</li>
                                    <li>0 comely lass ! even in the rainy seasons the clouds move about in the side ridges alone of the Himalayas.</li>
                                    <li>0 gentle lady, the clouds usually come only upto the foot of Kailasa. They never go above it.</li>
                                    <li>The clouds never go above the mountain Sumeru. The clouds Puskara Avartaka etc. reach the foot of Jambu  (and return) .</li>
                                    <li>Of these mountains I have mentioned you can choose one for residence as you desire. Please tell me quickly where you wish to reside.</li>
                                    <li>On the Himalayan mountains, songs exciting your curiosity and enthusiastic gaiety shall be sung by clusters and swarms of bees with sweet humming sounds as they play
                                    about as they please.</li>
                                    <li>On that mountain at the time when you wish to sport about, the Siddha women will gaily offer you a seat on the jewel-studded platform and gladly present you with
                                    fruits and other gifts.</li>
                                    <li>The daughters of the king of serpents, the mountain damsels, the Naga ladies and the Turanga-Mukhis will assist you in their excited flutter in congratulating you.</li>
                                    <li>Seeing your face of unequalled splendour and  beauty and your body of uncommon lustre, the celestial ladies there, despising their own beauty and lacking in interest
                                    in their own qualities will begin to stare at you with winkless eyes.</li>
                                    <li> Menaka,<noteref3_note3footer>(3) - (279)</note> the wife of the king of mountains famous in the three worlds for her beauty and good qualities will delight you very much through words of
                                    entreaties.</li>
                                    <li>The honourable ladies of Himalaya's harem will cause immense pleasure to your gracious Self. They will
                                    impart you useful instruction, though you need none, with pleasure every day.</li>
                                    <li>0 beloved, do you wish to go to the Himalayas, the king of mountains wherein there is spring for ever, which abounds in hedges and groves where the cuckoos coo in
                                    diverse pleasing ways and which contains many lakes filled with cool water and hundreds of lotuses.</li>
                                    <li>It is of full grassy plains and trees that yield everything one desires and hence on a par with Kalpa<noteref4_note4footer>(4) - (280)</note> trees.
                                    You can see plenty of flowers, horses, elephants and cows there.</li>
                                    <li>There in the Himalayas even the beasts of prey are calm. It is the abode of many sages and ascetics. It is an  abode of devas and many deer move about in it.</li>
                                    <li>It shines with ramparts of crystals, gold and silver. It is lustrous with the lakes-Manasa and others.</li>
                                    <li>It abounds in buds and full-blown lotuses with golden stalks studded with gems. Crocodiles, sharks and  tortoises abound in the Jakes.</li>
                                    <li>0 Goddess of devas, there are many beautiful blue lotuses emitting sweet fragrance. On the banks there are many grass lands, small and big trees and the saffron
                                    flowers increasing the fragrance of the waters with which the lakes are fulL</li>
                                    <li>The Apricot tree seems to dance with their  oscillating branches. They seem to be fanning the self-born  god of love. There are Sarasa birds and the intoxicated
                                    Cakravaka birds heightening its beauty.</li>
                                    <li>he different parts of the mountain Meru seem to be echoing the pleasing sweet sounds of bees etc.  which cause the incitement of love of the guardians of the
                                    quarters viz. Indra, Kubera, Yama, Varu:Q.a, Agni, Nirrti,
                                    Marut (Wind )<noteref1_note1footer>(5) - (281)</note> and the Supreme lord (Isa). Heaven, the abode of the Devas is stationed on the summits of the Meru
                                    wherein the cities of the guardians of the quarters are also situated. They are brilliant. Beautiful celestial damsels, Rambha, Saci, Menaka<noteref6_note1footer>(6) - (282)</note> and others heighten their glory.</li>
                                    <li>Do you wish to sport about on this great mountain which is very beautiful and which appears to contain the essence of all mountains ?</li>
                                    <li>There, the Queen Saci attended by her chaperons and celestial damsels will assist you always.</li>
                                    <li>Or do you wish to have an abode in my own Kailasa, the great mountain affording shelter to the good and enhanced in beauty by the luminous city of Kubera ?<noteref7_note7footer>(7) - (283)</note></li>
                                    <li> 0 beautiful lady, tell me quickly where do you wish to stay among these places, whether in Kailasa which is pure and holy by virtue of the river Ganga lustrous
                                    like the full moon or in the beautiful mountain Meru wherein the maidens of the sages recite and chant hymns in the caves and ridges or in places full of various deer and
                                    hundreds of lotus lakes. I shall make arrangements for your residence. </li>
                                    <em><span style="font-weight:900;color:white;text-shadow: 1px 1px 2px grey;background-color:silver;font-size:x-large">Shree Brahma said:  </span>
                                    <li>When Siva said thus, Sati slowly told lord Siva revealing her desire. </li>
                                    <em><span style="font-weight:900;color:crimson;text-shadow: 3px 3px 2px pink;background-color:orange;font-size:x-large">Sati said:  </span>
                                    <li>I wish to stay only on the Himalayas along with you. You please make arrangements for a residence on that mountain at once. </li>                            
                                    <em><span style="font-weight:900;color:white;text-shadow: 1px 1px 2px grey;background-color:silver;font-size:x-large">Shree Brahma said:  </span>
                                    <liOn hearing her words, Siva was fascinated and he went to the summit of the Himalayas along with her.</li>
                                    <li>He reached the beautiful summit where the Siddha<noteref8_note8footer>(8) - (284)</note> ladies resided, which could not be reached by birds
                                    and which shone with lakes and forests.</li>
                                    <li>The top was of variegated colours as of various gems, embellished by lotuses of diverse forms, shapes and lustre. Siva in the company of Sati reached that top which
                                    shone like the rising sun.</li>
                                    <li>On the top of the mountain near the city of Himalaya, Siva sported about for a long time in the company  of Sati. It was a very beautiful place which abounded in
                                    crystalline clouds. It shone with grassy plains and plenty of  trees. There were various flowers in abundance. It had  many lakes. The boughs of the full-blown and blossomed
                                    trees were surrounded by humming bees. Lotuses and blue  lilies were in full bloom. Different kinds of birds flew there, such as-Oakravaka Kadamba, swans, geese, the intoxicated
                                    Sarasas, cranes, the peacocks etc. The sweet note of the male cuckoo reverberated there. Many kinds of semidivine beings the Asvamukhas285, the Siddhas, the Apsaras, the Guhyakas,
                                    etc. roamed there. Their women-folk, the Vidyadharis, the  Kinnaris and the mountain lasses played about here and
                                    there. The celestial damsels played on their Jutes, tabours
                                    and drums and danced with enthusiasm. Thus the top of
                                    the mountain abounded in beautiful women, beautiful lakes,
                                    fragrant flowers and groves of full-blown flowers.</li>
                                    <li>In that heaven-like spot Siva sported about with
                                    Sati for ten thousand years according to divine calculation.</li>
                                    <li>Siva went from place to place. Sometimes He
                                    went to the top of Meru wherein Gods and Goddesses resided.
                                    He went to different continents, parks and forests on the
                                    earth. After visiting the different places He returned home
                                    and lived with Sati.</li>
                                    <li>Siva found place and pleasure only with Sati. He found no pleasure in sacrifices or the Vedas or penances.
                                    Day and night Sati stared into the face of Siva and He, The top was of variegated colours as of various  gems, embellished by lotuses of diverse forms, shapes and
                                    lustre. Siva in the company of Sati reached that top which shone like the rising sun.</li>
                                    <li>On the top of the mountain near the city of Himalaya, Siva sported about for a long time in the company of Sati. It was a very beautiful place which abounded in
                                    crystalline clouds. It shone with grassy plains and plenty of trees. There were various flowers in abundance. It had
                                    many lakes. The boughs of the full-blown and blossomed trees were surrounded by humming bees. Lotuses and blue lilies were in full bloom. Different kinds of birds flew there,
                                    such as-Oakravaka Kadamba, swans, geese, the intoxicated  Sarasas, cranes, the peacocks etc. The sweet note of the male
                                    cuckoo reverberated there. Many kinds of semidivine beings the Asvamukhas<noteref9_note9footer>(9) - (285)</note>, the Siddhas, the Apsaras, the Guhyakas,
                                    etc. roamed there. Their women-folk, the Vidyadharis, the Kinnaris and the mountain lasses played about here and
                                    there. The celestial damsels played on their Jutes, tabours and drums and danced with enthusiasm. Thus the top of
                                    the mountain abounded in beautiful women, beautiful lakes, fragrant flowers and groves of full-blown flowers.</li>
                                    <li>In that heaven-like spot Siva sported about with Sati for ten thousand years according to divine calculation.</li>
                                    <li>Siva went from place to place. Sometimes He went to the top of Meru wherein Gods and Goddesses resided.
                                    He went to different continents, parks and forests on the earth. After visiting the different places He returned home
                                    and lived with Sati.</li>
                                    <li>Siva found place and pleasure only with Sati. He found no pleasure in sacrifices or the Vedas or penances.
                                    Day and night Sati stared into the face of Siva and He, the great lord, stared into the face of Sati. Thus by their
                                    mutual association Kali and Siva nurtured the tree of love, sprinkling it with waters of emotion. </li>
                                    </ol> <a href=\'#top\'><strong>Back To Top</strong></a></p>`,
                                    notes: [`277. Ba<;lavamukha variously called Ba<;lavanala, Aurva etc. is a submarine fire, represented as a flame with a horse's head. According
                                        to PaurliJfiC Mythology it devours all things including the Gods, Asuras,
                                        and Raksasas at the dissolution of the Universe. `,
                                    `278. Pinaka-dhrk. It is the name of Siva derived from wielding a staff, bow or trident. `,
                                    `279· Menaka or Mena. She is the wife of Himavat and mother of Parvati and, Ganga and of a son named Mainaka. `,
                                    `280. One of the five trees of Indra's paradise fabled to fulfil all desires, the list being 
                                    <ul>
                                    <li>mandara (Erythrina stricta) with scarlet flowers in horizontal clusters at the ends of branches; its shade relieves one of physical ailments and mental stress; </li>
                                    <li>parijata (Nyctanthes arbor-tristis) with bark of gold, leaves of copper color, and fragrant, rejuvenate fruit; it arose out of the ocean of milk and was taken away by Indra to his paradise from where
                                     it was brought to Dvaraka by Lord Krsna at the instance of his wife Satyabhama. After the passing away of the Lord and the submerging of Dvaraka in the ocean, it was taken back to heaven;</li>
                                     <li>samtanaka, a tree of wonder having leaves which promote fertility in men; its identification remains obscure;</li>
                                     <li>haricandana or sandalwood (Santalum album) well known for its fragrance and cooling effect, it keeps evil spirits at bay; and</li>
                                     <li>kalpa vrksa or kalpa taru, the tree of eternity which emerged as a result of the churning of the ocean of milk; it was lifted to Svarga by Indra, and is frequently mentioned in Sanskrit literature for its wish-fulfilling quality.</li>
                                     </ul>`,
                                     `281. Reference is to Indra, Kubera, Yama, Varuna Agni Nirrti  Vayu and IMina who are the lords of eight quarters.  `,
                                    `282. Rambha, Saci, Menaka etc. are the heavenly nymphs famous for their personal charms. They are skilful in winning over the minds  even of the ascetics practising hard austerities. `,
                                    `283. Reference is to 'Alaka' also calkd Vasudhara, Vasusthali and Prabha which is the capital of Kubera and the abode of Gandharvas, Guhyakas, etc. See Note 226 `,
                                    `284. The Siddhas are a class of semidivine beings of great purity and holiness, said to be thousands in number.`,
                                    `285. The horse-faced Kinnaras and the Guhyakas are a class of demiGods who are attendants of Kubera and reside in the Himalayan caverns guarding his wealth. `]
                                 }
