                                     content: `
                                    <ol> <em><span style="font-weight:900;color:white;text-shadow: 1px 1px 2px grey;background-color:silver;font-size:x-large"font-size:larger">Shree Brahma said:  </span>
                                    <li> After sporting about like this till satiety with Siva, Sati became less attached.</li>
                                    <li>One day after delighting the lord with her  devotion and obeisance Sati, the daughter of Daksa spoke thus to Siva. </li>
                                    <em><span style="font-weight:900;color:crimson;text-shadow: 3px 3px 2px pink;background-color:orange;font-size:x-large">Sati said:  </span>
                                    <li>0 great lord, lord of lords and ocean of mercy, 0 great Yogin, the uplifter of the distressed, take pity on me.</li>
                                    <li>You are a great Purusa the lord, beyond Sattva, Rajas and Tamas. You are both Saguna and Nirguna.<noteref1_note1footer>(1) - (286)</note>
                                    You are a great lord, a cosmic witness, and free from aberration.</li>
                                    <li>I am blessed since I became your beloved wife sporting with you. 0 lord, you became my husband because of your love for your devotees.</li>
                                    <li>0 lord, after sporting with you for many years I have become fully satiated and now my mind is turned away from it.</li>
                                    <li>0 lord of gods, I wish to know the great pleasing principle whereby 0, Siva, all living beings surmount worldly miseries in a trice.</li>
                                    <li>0 lord, please explain that activity which enables people, to obtain the supreme region and free themselves from worldly bondage</li>
                                    <em><span style="font-weight:900;color:white;text-shadow: 1px 1px 2px grey;background-color:silver;font-size:x-large">Shree Brahma said:  </span>
                                    <li> 0 sage, the primordial Goddess asked Siva thus only for the sake of uplifting worldly creatures.</li>
                                    <li>On hearing that, lord Siva whose mind is engrossed in the practice of Yoga and who assumes physical bodies out of his own accord, spoke to Sati. </li>
                                    <em><span style="font-weight:900;color:darkblue;text-shadow: 3px 3px 2px white;background-color:skyblue;font-size:xx-large"> Lord Shiva said:  </span>
                                    <li>0 Goddess Sati, listen, I shall explain the great  principle whereby the remorseful creature becomes a liberated soul.</li>
                                    <li>0 great Goddess, know that the perfect knowledge is the great principle-the consciousness that "I am Brahman" in the perfect intellect where nothing else is
                                    remembered.</li>
                                    <li>This consciousness is very rare in the three worlds. 0 beloved, I am Brahman, the greatest of the great and very few are those who know my real nature.</li>
                                    <li>Devotion to me is considered as the bestower of worldly pleasures and salvation. It is achievable only by my grace. It is nine-fold.</li>
                                    <li>There is no difference between devotion and perfect knowledge. A person who is engrossed in devotion enjoys perpetual happiness. Perfect knowledge never
                                    descends in a vicious person averse to devotion.</li>
                                    <li>Attracted by devotion and as a result of its influence, 0 Goddess, I go even to the houses of the baseborn and outcastes. There is no doubt about it.</li>
                                    <li>Devotion is variously classified as attributive and attribute1ess, as conventional and natural, greater and lesser, perpetual and non-perpetual. There are six further
                                    subdivisions of the perpetual devotion. Scholars further classify it into enjoined and non-enjoined. Thus devotions are manifold which have been explained elsewhere.</li>
                                    <li>0 beloved, sages have explained that the different kinds of devotion have nine ancillary adjuncts. 0 daughter of Daksa I shall narrate them to which you listen with love.</li>
                                    <li>According to scholars 0 Goddess, the nine ancillary adjuncts are :-listening, eulogising, remembering, ·serving, surrendering, worshipping, saluting, friendliness and
                                    dedication. 0 Siva (Sati), its further subdivisions too have been explained.</li>
                                    <li>0 Goddess, listen to the characteristics of these  nine adjuncts separately. By listening is meant the imbibing of my stories that bestow worldly pleasures and salvation,
                                    with great devotion, in steady posture.</li>
                                    <li>After conceiving in the mind the details of my manifestations and activities, loudly and cheerfully, proclaiming the same in order to eulogise me is what is called
                                    eulogising.</li>
                                    <li>0 Goddess, after realising me to be all-pervading  a feeling of fearlessness is what is called remembering.</li>
                                    <li>The service rendered to the godhead commencing at the early dawn, with mind, speech, hands and feet is what is called serving.</li>
                                    <li>Surrendering oneself in the service of the godhead who is worthy of being served and serving with all the sense-organs feeling hearty sense of elation is what is called
                                    surrendering.</li>
                                    <li>Offering sixteen types of service to me, the upreme soul, in accordance with one's capacity is called worshipping. The sixteen types of service are Padya<noteref2_note2footer>(2) - (287)</note>
                                    etc.</li>
                                    <li> Meditating in the mind, repeating the mantras  and touching the ground with eight limbs<noteref3_note3footer>(3) - (288)</note> is called saluting.</li>
                                    <li>The belief-"Whatever god bestows on me, good or bad, is for my welfare" -is the characteristic sign of  friendliness.</li>
                                    <li>Dedicating everything, the body and other possessions, for the propitiation of the godhead and retaining nothing for oneself is called dedication.</li>
                                    <li>hese nine adjuncts to the devotion to me, cause  perfect knowledge, bestow wordly pleasures and salvation and are pleasing to me. </li>
                                    <li>The further subdivisions in the adjuncts are numerous. Nurturing the Bilva tree etc. can be included therein. They shall be thought of by the devotee himself.</li>
                                    <li>0 beloved, thus my devotion with various adjuncts and ancillaries, is contributory to salvation since it is  productive of perfect Knowledge and Detachment. It is the
                                    most excellent path.</li>
                                    <li>A true devotion is as endearing to me as to you. It is productive of the fruits of all rites for ever. He who has it in his mind is a great favourite of mine.</li>
                                    <li>There is no other path as easy and pleasing as devotion in the three worlds, 0 goddess of devas, in all the four Yugas generally and in the Kaliyuga particularly.</li>
                                    <li>Knowledge (Jniana) and Detachment (Vairagya) have grown old and have lost their lustre in the Kali Age. They have become decayed and worn-out as the people who
                                    can grasp them are rare.</li>
                                    <li>In the Kali age as in all the four Yugas there is immediate and visible benefit in devotion. I am subservient to a devotee in view of the power of devotion.</li>
                                    <li>I always assist a man endowed with devotion and remove his obstacles. A person devoid of devotion is worthy of being punished. There is no doubt about it.</li>
                                    <li>I am the protector· of my devotees. For the  protection of a devotee of mine I burnt the God of death, 0 goddess, in the fire emerging from my eyes.</li>
                                    <li>For the sake of a devotee of mine I became very furious with the sun formerly. I over-powered him with  my trident.</li>
                                    <li>I was not a party to the evil actions of Ravana  (though he was my devotee). For the sake of another  devotee I discarded Ravana with all his followers.</li>
                                    <li>0 goddess, for the sake of a devotee, I angrily  expelled Vyasa when he had a vicious thought, from Kasi after punishing him duly through Nandin.</li>
                                    <li>Why shall I say more, 0 Goddess ? I am always subservient to a devotee, always under the control of a person who practises devotion. There ·is no doubt
                                    in this. </li>
                                    <em><span style="font-weight:900;color:white;text-shadow: 1px 1px 2px grey;background-color:silver;font-size:x-large"font-size:larger">Shree Brahma said:  </span>
                                    <li>On hearing this greatness of devotion, Sati, the daughter of Daksa was delighted much and bowed to Siva with pleasure.</li>
                                    <li>0 sage, again she asked with great devotion more about the subject as explained in the Sastras which is pleasing and conducive to the uplift of all creatures.</li>
                                    <li>She enquired about topics on virtue and righteous living, uplighting the creatures and the sacred lore on Yantras  and Mantras<noteref4_note4footer>(4) - (289)</note> together with their greatness.</li>
                                    <li>On hearing the enquiry of Sati, Siva was delighted and He narrated them with pleasure in their entirety for raising the worldly creatures.</li>
                                    <li>The sacred lore bearing on the subject, the glory and greatness of the illustrious lord, Siva explained Himself with Yantras, with their five adjuncts.</li>
                                    <li>He told her legendary stories, the greatness of the votaries, the norms of peoples of different castes and stages in life and the duties of kings, 0 great sage.</li>
                                    <li>The duties of sons, wives etc. and their greatness, the imperishable system of Varnas and Asramas<noteref5_note5footer>(5) - (290)</note>, the medical
                                    lore, and the astral lore, all beneficent to worldly creatures
                                    were. explained by him.</li>
                                    <li>Out of compassion for her, the great lord explained the science of palmistry and similar other lores to her.</li>
                                    <li>Thus Sati and Siva who are intrinsically the  Supreme Brahman, who are the bestowers of happiness on the three worlds. who are omniscient, who are bent upon rendering help to the people, who appear as the personification of
                                    good qualities sported about in Kailasa, in the Himalayas and other places. </li></ol> <a href=\'#top\'><strong>Back To Top</strong></a></p>`,
                                    notes: [`286. Siva is conceived as Saguna (possessed of attribute-s), personal deity who responds to prayer, bestows grace or enters into history. He
                                        is conceived also as Nirgu:Q.a when in the devotee's state of mental spiritual enlightenment (Jniana) he is identical with his self. `,
                                    `287. On the sixteen acts of worship `,
                                    `288. On the Astanga pranama `,
                                    `289.. unclear - preserved for numerical continuity `,
                                     `290. The laws relating to four castes-Brahmana, Kshatriya, VaiSya and Sudra and to four stages of life-the student, the householder the anchorite and the religious mendrcant are expounded in the of
                                     Manu and are applicable to Indian Society alone. `]
                                 }
