                                     content: `
                                    <ol> <em><span style="font-weight:900;color:white;text-shadow: 1px 1px 2px grey;background-color:silver;font-size:x-large">Shree Brahma said:  </span>
                                    <li>Once a great sacrifice was started by Daksa, 0 sage. To partake in that sacrifice, the celestial and terrestrial sages and devas were invited by Siva (=Daksa?) and they reached the
                                    place being deluded by Siva's Maya.</li>
                                    <li>Agastya, Kasyapa, Atri, Vamadeva, Bhrgu, Dadhici, the revered Vyasa, Bharadvaja, Gautama, Paila, Parasara,
                                    Garga, Bhargava, Kakubha, Sita Sumantu, Trika, Karika, Vaisampayana and many others .along with their sons and  wives arrived at the sacrifice of son.</li>
                                    <li>All the devas, the guardians of the quarters of rising fortune, the subordinate devas with their offers of help and service attended the sacrifice.</li>
                                    <li>From Satyaloka, I, the creator of the universe, was duly lauded and taken there along with my sons, followers and the embodied forms of the Vedas etc. </li>
                                    <li>Visnu was duly requested, respected and brought to the place of sacrifice from Vaikuntha<noteref1_note1footer>(1) - (300)</note> along with his aide-decamp and followers.</li>
                                    <li>Similarly others too, equally deluded, came to the sacrifice. Then Daksa who was ill disposed towards Siva received them hospitably.</li>
                                    <li>Large divine mansions of great value and brilliant lustre were erected by Tvastr<noteref2_note2footer>(2) - (301)</note> and assigned to them by Daksa</li>
                                    <li>In all those places they stationed themselves in a befitting manner after being duly honoured. They shone along with Visnu and me.</li>
                                    <li>In that sacrifice that was being performed in that holy place of Kanakhala, <noteref3_note3footer>(3) - (302)</note> Bhrgu and other sages were made
                                    Ritviks by him (Daksa).</li>
                                    <li>Visnu himself was the presiding officer along with the Maruts. I was the Brahma (a special officiating deity)  the director and guide for Vedic rituals.</li>
                                    <li>he guardians of the quarters became the gatekeepers and watchmen. They were well-equipped in arms and had many attendants to assist them. They were very
                                    enthusiastic.</li>
                                    <li>In that altar, sacrifice itself was present in its  beautiful embodied form. The excellent sages became the holders of the Vedas.</li>
                                    <li>The sacrificial .fire evinced its diverse forms in a thousand ways, during the sacrificial festivities, in order to
                                    receive the sacrificial offerings of Daksa</li>
                                    <li>There were eightysix thousand Ritviks <noteref4_note4footer>(4) - (303)</note> in the performance of the sacrifice and sixtyfour thousand Udgatrs.
                                    The celestial sages Narada and others acted as Adhvaryus and Hotrs. They too were as many. The seven sages (jointly and) severally repeated the Saman hymns.</li>
                                    <li>In his great sacrifice Daksa extended his invitation to Gandharvas, Vidyadharas, Siddhas, Adityas, all the
                                    innumerable Nagas along with their followers and sacrificial ritualists.</li>
                                    <li>Brahminical, Royal and celestial sages, kings, with
                                    their friends, ministers, armies etc, Vasus<noteref5_note5footer>(5) - (305)</note> and other chief Ganadevatas-all of them were invited by him in the sacrifice.</li>
                                    <li>With the proper initiation, . tying of the holy thread round his wrist and Svastyayana<noteref6_note6footer>(6) - (306)</note> rites duly performed, Daksa along with his wife, shone well.</li>
                                    <li>Daksa the evil-minded, did not invite Siva for that sacrifice, deciding that He was not worthy of taking part in the sacrifice because He was a Kapalin<noteref7_note5footer>(7) - (307)</note></li>
                                    <li>In view of the fact that Sati was the wife of Kapalin, she was not invited, though she was his beloved daughter, by Daksa who was blind to her qualities.</li>
                                    <li>While the great festivities in the sacrifice of Daksa were being celebrated those who had assembled for the same were engrossed in their respective activities.</li>
                                    <li>In the meantime, Dadhici<noteref8_note8footer>(8) - (308)</note>a devotee of Siva, realising that lord Siva was not there became dispirited and spoke thus. </li>
                                    <em><span style="font-weight:900;color:#334443;font-size:larger">Dadhici Said:  </span>
                                    <li>0 ye all ! celestial sages and others, pay heed to my words. Why has not Siva taken part in the festivities of this sacrifice ?</li>
                                    <li>Of course, the chiefs of devas, the great sages and the guardians of the quarters have all come. Yet the sacrifice cannot be perfect and complete without the noble-souled,
                                    trident-holder Siva.</li>
                                    <li>The bull-bannered, blue-necked eternal Purusa the great Isa is not seen here. Great scholars have affirmed, that all auspicious results happen due to Him alone.</li>
                                    <li>0 Daksa, if accepted by Triyambaka all inauspicious things become auspicious and fresh auspicious things take shape which will be greater than the greatest in a trice.</li>
                                    <li>Hence the invitation to the great Siva shall be extended by you yourself immediately or by Brahma or by Visnu the lord.</li>
                                    <li>By all means Siva shall be brought here by you along with Indra, the guardians of the quarters, the brahmins and the Siddhas in order to make the sacrifice complete
                                    and perfect.</li>
                                    <li>All of you shall go where He is stationed.- Immediately bring Siva along with Sati.</li>
                                    <li>0 lords of Devas, everything shall be sanctified through Siva, the supreme Self. If the consort of Siva, the  great Being, comes here, everything will be all right.</li>
                                    <li>Since all merits accrue from thinking upon Him and repeating His names, the bull-bannered deity shall be  brought with aU efforts.</li>
                                    <li>If Siva comes here, the sacrifice will become sanctified, or it will remain incomplete and imperfect. I am  telling you the truth.</li>
                                    <li>On hearing his words, the foolish and evil-minded  Daksa became furious in a trice and said mockingly. </li>
                                    <em><span style="font-weight:900;color:maroon;font-size:larger"> Daksa said:  </span>
                                    <li>Visnu who is the prime cause of all deities and in whom the eternal virtue resides has been invoked here by me. What is it that the sacrificial rite lacks in ?</li>
                                    <li>Visnu in whom all the Vedas, sacrifices and the different rites are founded has graced this place by his presence.</li>
                                    <li>Brahma, the grandfather of the worlds, has come here from Satyaloka along with the Vedas, Upanisads and the Agamas. </li>
                                    <li>Similarly, the king of devas himself has Come along with all the devas. You too, the sages free from sins, have come.</li>
                                    <li>Whoever is worthy of being included in the sacrifice and deserves honour has come. You all know the Vedic texts and their meanings. You all are steady in your rites.</li>
                                    <li>Of what avail is Siva to us in this place ? 0 brahmin, of course I have given my daughter to Him but  that was because I was persuaded by Brahma.</li>
                                    <li>0 brahmin, this Siva is not a man of nobility. He has neither father nor mother. He is the lord of goblins, ghosts and spirits and is incorrigible.</li>
                                    <li>He is a haughty self-conceited fool with false prestige and hostility. He is unworthy of this sacred rite. Hence he is not invited by me.</li>
                                    <li>Therefore you shall never make such statements as these henceforth. My great sacrifice has to be made fruitful  by all of you. </li>
                                    <em><span style="font-weight:900;color:white;text-shadow: 1px 1px 2px grey;background-color:silver;font-size:x-large">Shree Brahma said:  </span>
                                    <li>AOn hearing those words, Dadhici spoke aloud within the hearing of devas and sages. His words were pregnant
                                    with meaning.  </li>
                                    <em><span style="font-weight:900;color:#334443;font-size:larger">Dadhici Said:  </span>
                                    <li>This sacrifice has become "Non-sacrifice" without the presence of Siva. Indeed your destruction is imminent in this very sacrifice.</li>
                                    <li>...</li>
                                    <li>Saying this, Dadhici walked out of the sacrifice of and immediately returned to his hermitage.</li>
                                    <li>Then some important devotees of Siva who were initiated in the Saiva cult cursed Daksa and returned to their respective abodes.</li>
                                    <li>When the sage Dadhici and others staged a walkout, the evil-minded Daksa inimical to Siva, said mocking at them</li>
                                    <em><span style="font-weight:900;color:maroon;font-size:larger"> Daksa said:  </span>
                                    <li>Gone is that brahmin favourite of Siva named Dadhici and others too of his ilk have gone out of my sacrifice.</li>
                                    <li> This has become good. I approve of this always. 0 Indra, devas and sages, I am telling you the truth.</li>
                                    <li>They are slow-witted and senseless. They are rogues indulging in false deliberations and discussions. They
                                    are out of the Vedic circle. These men of evil conduct shall  be eschewed from sacrificial rites.</li>
                                    <li>You all, brahmins, sages and devas with at
                                    the head shall make my sacrifice fruitful. </li>
                                     <em><span style="font-weight:900;color:white;text-shadow: 1px 1px 2px grey;background-color:silver;font-size:x-large">Shree Brahma said:  </span>
                                    <li>On hearing these words, the celestial sages deluded by Siva's Maya performed the worship of the deities in that sacrifice. 0 great sage, I have thus explained how
                                    the sacrifice had been cursed. Now I shall explain how the sacrifice was destroyed. </li>
                                   </ol> <a href=\'#top\'><strong>Back To Top</strong></a></p>`,
                                    notes: [`300. Vaikntha, also called Vaibhra, is the abode of Visnu variously described as situated on the eastern peak of Mount Meru or in the
                                        Northern ocean. `,
                                        `301. TvaHr is identified with Visvakarman, the divine architrct. `,
                                    `302. Kanakhala is a sacred town, near Haradvara, on the Ganges where Daksa performed the great sacrifice in which Sati burnt herself. The river Ganga is held very sacred at Kanakhala.`,
                                    `303. The priests (Ftvijas) participating in the Vedic sacrifices are usual four in number. They are (r) Rotr, Adhvaryu, Udgatr and
                                    Brahman corresponding to the four Vedas- :Rig, Yajus, Saman an  Atharvan respectively. Each of the priests has three companions or helpers, the total no. is sixteen viz. Hot:r-Maitdivarul)a, Acchavaka,
                                    Ot:ayastut; Adhvaryu-Pratiprasthatr, Unnetr; Udgatr- Prastotr, Pratihart:r, Nestr, Subrahmal).ya and Btahman-Brahman2.cchamsin, AgnidLra, Potr. `,
                                    `304.`,
                                    `305.`,
                                    `306 A set of Vedic Mantras recited for causing prosperity and good fortune`,
                                    `307. Siva is called Kapalin for He bears skulls of men (Kapala) as ornament`,
                                    `308.  Dadhici `
                                    ]
                                 }
