                                     content: `
                                     <ol> <em><span style="font-weight:900;color:white;text-shadow: 1px 1px 2px grey;background-color:silver;font-size:x-large">Shree Brahma said:  </span>
                                    <li> On hearing these words of lord Siva with great respect, Virabhadra was highly delighted. He bowed to Him.</li>
                                    <li>Receiving his command, with his head bowed down  in reverence, Virabhadra set off immediately to the place of sacrifice.</li>
                                    <li>To add lustre to the campaign, Siva sent crores of Ganas, very valorous and equal to the fire of dissolution.</li>
                                    <li>Those powerful Ganas enthusiastic and gay both preceded and followed Virabhadra.</li>
                                    <li>All the personal attendants of Kalakala assuming the form of Rudra accompanied Virabhadra in their hundreds and thousands.</li>
                                    <li>Accompanied by these Ganas, the noble-souled Virabhadra who had the same dress, features and embellishments as Siva went ahead in a chariot. ·He had a thousand
                                    arms each like hoods of the serpent king. He was powerful and terrifying.</li>
                                    <li>The chariots numbered as many as two thousand Nalvas<noteref1_note1footer>(1) - (322)</note>
                                    of land could contain. Ten thousand lions pulled the chariots strenuously. </li>
                                    <li>Many strong lions, tigers, crocodiles, huge fishes and thousands of elephants constituted his body-guard.</li>
                                    <li>When Virabhadra  set-off quickly for slaying Daksa,  a shower of flowers fell there let loose by the divine Kalpa tree.</li>
                                    <li>During the festivities of their march, the Ganas eulogised the heroic Virabhadra who was carrying out the job of Siva and they exhibited their enthusiasm.</li>
                                    <li>Mahakali went ahead for the destruction of accompanied by nine Durgas<noteref2_note2footer>(2) - (324)</note> Viz:-Kali, Katyayani,
                                    Isani, Cammunda, Mundamardini, Bhadrakali, Bhadra, Tvarita and Vaisnavi and the goblins.</li>
                                    <li>Eager in executing the command of Siva, they ccompanied the marching heroes-:Dakini, Sakini, Bhutas, Pramathas, Guhyakas, Parpatas, Catakas, BrahmaBhairavas and 
                                    Ksetrapalas and set out quickly for the destruction of sacrifice.</li>
                                    <li>The host of Yoginis<noteref3_note3footer>(3) - (325)</note> with their sixty four groups set out angrily and hurriedly to destroy Dak§a's sacrifice.</li>
                                    <li>0 Narada, listen to the numerical strength of the most important and courageous of those groups.</li>
                                    <li>The chief of Ganas-Sankukarna went ahead with ten crores of his attendants; with ten crores and Vikrta with eight crores</li>
                                    <li>Kapalisa with five crores and the Sandaraka group with six crores; Kotikunda with crores of crores.</li>
                                    <li>Vistamba the most excellent of the Ganas, went with sixtyfour crores of heroes. 0 dear, Sannada and Pippala went with a thousand crores.</li>
                                    <li>Avesana went with eight crores and Candratapana too with eight crores. Mahavesa, the chief of Ganas, was accompanied by a thousand crores.</li>
                                    <li>0 sage, Kundi the most excellent of the Ganas and Pavataka went each with twelve crores in order to destroy Daksa's sacrifice.</li>
                                    <li>Kala, Kalaka and Mahakala went to the sacrifice of Daksa with a hundred crores.</li>
                                    <li>Agnikrt with hundred crores; Agnimukha with a crore; Adityamiirdha and Ghanavaha each with a crore.</li>
                                    <li>Sannaha with hundred crores; Kumuda with a crore; Amogha and Kokila the chief of Gai).as each with a crore of crores.</li>
                                    <li>Kasthagudha, Sukesi, and Sumantraka the chief of Gainas, 0 dear, each went with sixtyfour crores.</li>
                                    <li>Kakapadodara and Santanaka both excellent chiefs of Ganas went with sixty crores each.</li>
                                    <li> Mahabala as well as Purigava went with nine crores each.</li>
                                    <li>0 dear, the chief of Ganas, Madhupiriga was the leader of ninety crores. Purnaabhadra also started with as
                                    many attendants.</li>
                                    <li>Caturvaktra, the chief of Ganas, started with hundred crores.</li>
                                    <li>Virupaksa, the lord of Gai).as, with sixtyfour crores. So also the chiefs of Ganas Talaketu, Sadasya, and Pancasya.</li>
                                    <li>0 sage, Sarilvartaka, Kulisa, Svayamprabhu, Lokantaka, Dipditma, Daityantaka, Bhrrigiriti, Devadevapriya,
                                    Asani and Bhalaka each went with sixtyfour thousand Ganas.</li>
                                    <li>Thus at the bidding of Siva, the heroic Virabhadra went ahead followed by crores and crores, thousands and thousands, hundreds and hundreds of Ganas.</li>
                                    <li>The hero was accompanied by thousands of crores of goblins, and three crores of canine species born of the
                                    hair of Siva. He went ahead quickly.</li>
                                    <li>Trumpets and drums sounded loudly. Conchs blew in diverse ways. Horns of all kinds were blown.</li>
                                    <li>In that joyous festivity various musical instruments were played in a pleasing manner.</li>
                                    <li>While the march of Virabhadra was in progress, 0 great sage, many pleasing fortutious omens occurred. </li></ol> 
                                    <a href=\'#top\'><strong>Back To Top</strong></a></p>`,
                                    notes: [`322. Nalva is a measure of distance equal to four hundred (or according to some authorities one hundred four) cubits. `,
                                    `Nine Durgas are variously named in the Puranas. For instance, compare the names of nine Durgas in the Markandeya Purana. `,
                                    `325. Yoginis are female sorceresses attendant on Durga. They are represented as sixty-four in number. `]
                                 }
                             ]
