                                { 
                                     subTitle: '',
                                     content: `
                                     <ol>  <em><span style="font-weight:900;color:maroon;font-size:larger"> Daksa said:  </span>
                                     <li> 0 Hari, Vi:p,1u, lord of devas, friend of the poor, storehouse of mercy, you must protect me and my sacrifice.</li>
                                     <li>You are the guardian of sacrifice. You are identical with the activity of sacrifice, the performer of sacrifice; 0 lord, be merciful, let not the sacrifice be destroyed. </li>
                                     <em><span style="font-weight:900;color:white;text-shadow: 1px 1px 2px grey;background-color:silver;font-size:x-large">Shree Brahma said:  </span>
                                    <li> Thus submitting entreaties of diverse sorts with great respect, in his mental agitation due to fear, he fell at his feet.</li>
                                    <li>Visnu raised Daksa of agitated mind and on hearing the words of that evil-minded one, Visnu remembered Siva.</li>
                                    <li>After remembering Siva his own lord, Visnu, the knower of Siva's principles, said thus, addressing Daksa </li>
                                    <em><span style="font-weight:900;color:maroon;text-shadow: 3px 3px 2px pink;background-color:orange;font-size:x-large">Shree Vishnu said:  </span>
                                    <li>Listen, 0 Daksa I shall explain everything true to fact; listen to my words which are as efficacious as mantras, beneficent and pleasing.</li>
                                    <li>Not knowing the principle of Siva, the great Self and lord of everything, you have insulted Him.</li>
                                    <li>By insulting Him, not only does every activity become futile in every respect but also it engenders adversities at every· step.</li>
                                    <li>Poverty, death and fear, these three take place when people worthy of worship are not worshipped and when undeserving people are honoured.</li>
                                    <li>Hence with all efforts, the bull-bannered deity shall be respected and revered. A great terror has befallen us because lord Siva has been dishonoured here.</li>
                                    <li>AI though we are all lords, we are unable to accomplish anyything due to your misdeeds. It is a fact I am mentioning. </li>
                                    <em><span style="font-weight:900;color:white;text-shadow: 1px 1px 2px grey;background-color:silver;font-size:x-large">Shree Brahma said:  </span>
                                    <li>On hearing these words of Visnu, Daksa began to ponder. He sat quietly on the ground with his face turned pale.</li>
                                    <li>Meanwhile Virab>hadra, the leader of the Ganas, sent by Rudra, came to the place of sacrifice accompanied by his army.</li>
                                    <li>Some of his attendants followed him closely; some came through the sky and others came from the different quarters and sub-quarters. At the bidding of Siva,
                                    these innumerable heroic, fearless Ganas came there roaring like lions.</li>
                                    <li>By that great sound, the three worlds echoed and the quarters were plunged in darkness.</li>
                                    <li>The whole earth containing the seven continents shook with fear. All the oceans, forests and mountains were  excessively agitated.</li>
                                    <li>On seeing that vast army of destructive potentiality, devas and others were quite surprised.</li>
                                    <li>On seeing the enterprising activity of the army, Daksa's face turned red with agitation. He fell at the feet of Visnu
                                    straight like a staff, prostrated at his feet, along with his wife and said thus. </li>
                                    <em><span style="font-weight:900;color:maroon;font-size:larger"> Daksa said:  </span>
                                    <li>Depending upon you, this great sacrifice was started by me. 0 Visnu great lord, you are the final authority in the matter of realising good rites. </li>
                                    <li>0 Visnu you are the cosmic witness of sacred rites and the protector of sacrifices. You are the saviour of Vedic virtue, 0 great lord.</li>
                                    <li>Hence, 0 lord, you shall offer protection to my sacrifice here. Who else, other than you, is competent for it ? You are the lord of all. </li>
                                    <em><span style="font-weight:900;color:white;text-shadow: 1px 1px 2px grey;background-color:silver;font-size:x-large">Shree Brahma said:  </span>
                                    <li>On hearing these piteous words of Daksa, Visnu spoke enJightening the former who was averse to Siva's principles. </li>
                                    <em><span style="font-weight:900;color:maroon;text-shadow: 3px 3px 2px pink;background-color:orange;font-size:x-large">Shree Vishnu said:  </span>
                                    <li> 0 Daksa, protection shall be offered to your sacrifice. My promise of protecting Dharma is truly well known.</li>
                                    <li>You have stated the truth, but you have transgressed the same. 0 Daksa listen, I shall tell you. Cast off your cruelty.</li>
                                    <li> What transpired at Naimisa<noteref1_note1footer>(1) - (326)</note> the holy place in a surprisingly mysterious manner is evidently not remembered
                                    by you, 0 Daksa. Did you forget it in your evil way ?</li>
                                    <li>Who can save you from Rudra's anger ? 0 Daksa, a person who protects you, the wicked one, finds no approval anywhere.</li>
                                    <li>An evil-minded man does not see what is good and what is not. A sacred action or rite cannot be efficacious  always.</li>
                                    <li>You must know that to be your duty which is naturally efficacious. Except Siva none can be the bestower of action.</li>
                                    <li>Siva bestows the fruit of the actions upon the person who is tranquil on accouut of devotion to the lord
                                    and whose mind is fixed in him alone.</li>
                                    <li>Depending upon Knowledge alone if they eschew  devotion to God they will fall into hell .and remain there
                                    for hundreds of crores of Kalpas. </li>
                                    <li>Those who solely depend on actions are bound by its nooses, are born in lives after lives and are finally
                                    scorched and tortured in hells.</li>
                                    <li>Here, Virabhadra, the chief of Rudra's attendants, who suppresses all his enemies and who is born of the fire
                                    of Rudra's anger has now come to the sacrificial yard.</li>
                                    <li>There is no doubt in this that he has come for destroying us. There is nothing impossible for him to do, whatever it may be really.</li>
                                    <li>It is certain that this great lord will become tranquil only after burning us all</li>
                                    <li> Since by my mistake I have transgressed the affirmation of lord Siva, I too shall bear the miseries along with you.</li>
                                    <li>0 Daksa I have no power to prevent this since I have become an enemy of Siva by transgressing his affirmation.</li>
                                    <li>There can be no happiness to the enemies of Siva  in the three periods of time; misery has of necessity been invited by me along with you.</li>
                                    <li>My discus Sudarsana will not hit him. My discus  is Saiva {belonging to Siva) and it can cause the death of only non-Saivas.</li>
                                    <li>Even if Virabhadra had not been here, this discus would have killed us and returned to Siva.</li>
                                    <li>This discus has remained without killing me, although I had transgressed the avowal of Siva. It indicates
                                    that it is compassionate.</li>
                                    <li>Hereafter this discus will not stay with me. With its fiery effusions it will depart quickly.</li>
                                    <li>Even if he is worshipped and honoured by us with respect, Virabhadra will not protect us since he is extremely angry.</li>
                                    <li>A sudden dissolution of every one of us is imminent. Alas, it. ha-s already set upon us.</li>
                                    <li>There is none to offer us refuge in· the three worlds. Who can be the refuge of an enemy of Siva in this world?</li>
                                    <li>Even if the body undergoes destruction,. the torture at the hands of Yama<noteref1_note1footer>(1) - (327)</note> is in store for us. It is impossible
                                    to bear as it generates much misery.</li>
                                    <li>On seeing an enemy of Siva, Yama gnashes his teeth. He puts him in cauldrons of oil and not otherwise.</li>
                                    <li> Actually I was preparing to leave after an open declaration. Still I did not leave immediately by the contagious sin of this wicked person.</li>
                                    <li>Even if we flee from this place, Virabhadra the devotee of Siva, will drag and pull us by means of his weapons.</li>
                                    <li>Whether it is heaven or earth, Patala or any where else, it is not difficult for the weapons of Virabhadra to gain access there.</li>
                                    <li>Such is the power of everyone of the attendants  of the tride11t-bearing Rudra.</li>
                                    <li>Formerly at Kasi, Kalabhairava had plucked off the fifth head of Brahma playfully with the tip of his nail.</li>
                                    <li></li>
                                    <li>After saying this, Visnu resumed his seat, his lotusface showing signs of great fear. At the same time Virabhadra too reached the sacrificial platform.</li>
                                    <li>While was saying this, the gods and others
                                    saw the vast ocean of the army led by Virabhadra already come there </li>
                                    </ol> 
                                    <a href=\'#top\'><strong>Back To Top</strong></a></p>`,
                                    notes: [`326. Naimisa modern Nimsar, is a saered region of Uttara Pradda  in the district of Sitapur on the bank of Gomati.  `,
                                    `327. Yama: In Pauranic Mythology, Yama is the God who presides over the manes and rul.es the spirits of the dead. He is always represented as a terrible deity  afflicting tortures, called yatana, on departed sinful sp1nts. `]
                                 }
                             ]
